  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How strong is the Turkish passport?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Turkish passport provides visa-free or visa-on-arrival access to 110+ countries including Japan, Singapore, South Korea, most of South America, and many others. It doesn't include US or EU visa-free access, but opens many doors for citizens of more restrictive countries.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to live in Turkey after getting citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Turkish citizenship has no residency requirement after naturalization. You can live anywhere in the world. You must hold the property for 3 years, but don't need to live in it or even in Turkey. Many CBI citizens never actually reside in Turkey.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Turkish citizenship revocable?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If you sell property before the 3-year hold period, citizenship can be revoked. Also revocable for fraud or misrepresentation in the application. After 3 years, with proper documentation, citizenship is permanent. Dual citizenship is allowed—Turkey doesn't require you to renounce other nationalities.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about military service for males?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Turkish male citizens have military service obligation. However, naturalized citizens over 22 who haven't resided in Turkey can pay for exemption (~$10,000). Important to address this during application for male family members to avoid future complications.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I use cryptocurrency to invest?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The investment must be made through Turkish banking system with clear fund sourcing. While you can sell crypto elsewhere and transfer funds, the actual investment payment must be through proper banking channels. Source of funds documentation is required.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens to the property after 3 years?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After the 3-year hold period, the sale restriction (takyidat) is lifted. You can sell the property, keep it, or do whatever you wish. Citizenship remains permanent. Many investors sell and recoup most of their investment (minus transaction costs and any market changes).
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Turkey offers one of the fastest and most accessible Citizenship by Investment programs in the world. For $400,000 in real estate, you can obtain full citizenship and a Turkish passport in just 3-6 months—remarkable speed compared to other CBI programs that take 12-18+ months.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Turkish passport provides meaningful travel freedom (110+ countries), though it doesn't include US or EU visa-free access. For citizens of more restrictive countries, it represents a significant upgrade. The ability to hold dual citizenship makes it a valuable "Plan B" passport.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Consider the trade-offs: currency volatility, political uncertainty, and a 3-year property hold requirement. Turkey isn't EU, so it doesn't provide Schengen residence rights. But for speed, cost-effectiveness, and a functional second passport, Turkey is hard to beat. Healthcare is excellent and affordable—a bonus for those planning to spend time there.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
